{"title_page": "Arbaces", "text_new": "{{about||the Alix comics character|Arbac\u00e8s|the protagonist of the Jacobean play ''A King and No King''|A King and No King}}\n'''Arbaces''' was the name of more than one person of classical antiquity:\n\n==Founder of Median empire==\nAccording to [[Ctesias]], Arbaces was one of the generals of [[Sardanapalus]], king of [[Assyria]] and founder of the [[Medes|Median]] empire about 830 BC.{{sfn|Meyer|1911|p=322}}\n\nCtesias's whole history of the Assyrian and Median empires is absolutely fabulous; his Arbaces and his successors are not historical personages.{{sfn|Meyer|1911|p=322}} Mahmoud Omidsalar suggests that \"the very fact that all but one of the kings in Ctesias's list are not historical implies that these kings were legendary rulers who belonged to the ancient Iranian lore, and records of their exploits existed in some written form in the fifth century BC\"<ref name=Omidsalar>{{cite book|last1=Omidsalar|first1=Mahmoud|title=Poetics and Politics of Iran's National Epic, the Shahnameh|publisher=Palgrave MacMillan|isbn=978-0230113459|pages=35\u201336|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=1U9dAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT69&lpg=PT69&dq=Ctesias+royal+leather+records&source=bl&ots=bYNbh1BQIk&sig=RYnhHIAoJkJ-3Y-qOHxol6MuPrE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCEQ6AEwAGoVChMIn9HC9oWayAIVA1UUCh04VA07#v=onepage&q=Ctesias%20royal%20leather%20records&f=false}}</ref>\n\nFrom the inscriptions of [[Sargon II of Assyria]] it is known that one '''Arbaku''' of [[Arnashia]] was one of forty-five chiefs of Median districts who paid tribute to Sargon in 713 BC.{{sfn|Meyer|1911|p=322}} He was a satrap, who conspired against Sardanapalus, and founded the empire of Media on the ruins of the Assyrian kingdom.<ref>{{Citation |chapterurl=http://www.infoplease.com/dictionary/brewers/arbaces.html |chapter=Arbaces |title=Dictionary of Phrase and Fable |first=E. Cobham |last=Brewer |year=1894}}</ref>\n\nArbaces or Arbaku is also the [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]] spelling for the name of the 6th Century BC [[Medes|Median]] general, [[Harpagus]].\n\n==Median commander==\nAnother Arbaces was a commander in the army of [[Artaxerxes II of Persia]], which fought against his brother [[Cyrus the Younger]], in 401 BC. He was [[satrap]] of [[Media (region)|Media]].<ref>[[Xenophon]], ''[[Anabasis (Xenophon)|Anabasis]]'' 1.7.12, 7.8.25</ref>\n\n==Modern==\nArbaces is a character in ''[[The Last Days of Pompeii]]'', a book by [[Edward Bulwer-Lytton]] in the ''Pompeii Series''.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===External links===\n*[https://www.livius.org/ha-hd/harpagus/harpagus.html Harpagus according to Livius]\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Arbaces|volume=2|page=322|first=Eduard|last=Meyer|authorlink=Eduard Meyer}}\n*{{DGRBM|author=WS|title= Arbaces |volume=1|page=256|url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/m/moa/acl3129.0001.001/271}}\n\n[[Category:Ancient Assyrians]]\n[[Category:Median people]]\n\n\n{{Ancient-Greek-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{For2|the Alix comics character|[[Arbac\u00e8s]]|the protagonist of the Jacobean play ''A King and No King''|[[A King and No King]]}}\n'''Arbaces''' was the name of more than one person of classical antiquity:\n\n==Founder of Median empire==\nAccording to [[Ctesias]], Arbaces was one of the generals of [[Sardanapalus]], king of [[Assyria]] and founder of the [[Medes|Median]] empire about 830 BC.{{sfn|Meyer|1911|p=322}}\n\nCtesias's whole history of the Assyrian and Median empires is absolutely fabulous; his Arbaces and his successors are not historical personages.{{sfn|Meyer|1911|p=322}} Mahmoud Omidsalar suggests that \"the very fact that all but one of the kings in Ctesias's list are not historical implies that these kings were legendary rulers who belonged to the ancient Iranian lore, and records of their exploits existed in some written form in the fifth century BC\"<ref name=Omidsalar>{{cite book|last1=Omidsalar|first1=Mahmoud|title=Poetics and Politics of Iran's National Epic, the Shahnameh|publisher=Palgrave MacMillan|isbn=978-0230113459|pages=35\u201336|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=1U9dAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT69&lpg=PT69&dq=Ctesias+royal+leather+records&source=bl&ots=bYNbh1BQIk&sig=RYnhHIAoJkJ-3Y-qOHxol6MuPrE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCEQ6AEwAGoVChMIn9HC9oWayAIVA1UUCh04VA07#v=onepage&q=Ctesias%20royal%20leather%20records&f=false}}</ref>\n\nFrom the inscriptions of [[Sargon II of Assyria]] it is known that one '''Arbaku''' of [[Arnashia]] was one of forty-five chiefs of Median districts who paid tribute to Sargon in 713 BC.{{sfn|Meyer|1911|p=322}} He was a satrap, who conspired against Sardanapalus, and founded the empire of Media on the ruins of the Assyrian kingdom.<ref>{{Citation |chapterurl=http://www.infoplease.com/dictionary/brewers/arbaces.html |chapter=Arbaces |title=Dictionary of Phrase and Fable |first=E. Cobham |last=Brewer |year=1894}}</ref>\n\nArbaces or Arbaku is also the [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]] spelling for the name of the 6th Century BC [[Medes|Median]] general, [[Harpagus]].\n\n==Median commander==\nAnother Arbaces was a commander in the army of [[Artaxerxes II of Persia]], which fought against his brother [[Cyrus the Younger]], in 401 BC. He was [[satrap]] of [[Media (region)|Media]].<ref>[[Xenophon]], ''[[Anabasis (Xenophon)|Anabasis]]'' 1.7.12, 7.8.25</ref>\n\n==Modern==\nArbaces is a character in ''[[The Last Days of Pompeii]]'', a book by [[Edward Bulwer-Lytton]] in the ''Pompeii Series''.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===External links===\n*[https://www.livius.org/ha-hd/harpagus/harpagus.html Harpagus according to Livius]\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Arbaces|volume=2|page=322|first=Eduard|last=Meyer|authorlink=Eduard Meyer}}\n*{{DGRBM|author=WS|title= Arbaces |volume=1|page=256|url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/m/moa/acl3129.0001.001/271}}\n\n[[Category:Ancient Assyrians]]\n[[Category:Median people]]\n\n\n{{Ancient-Greek-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Simplified hatnote syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arbaces"}
